  "description": "Use this index to navigate by practice area and data outcome rather than by section order.\n¶Observation practice Intent: why you are observing matters Evidence: photos, sounds, and metadata Repeatability: temporal and spatial consistency ¶Reading pathways If you want to improve evidence quality: start with Evidence → Data quality → Identification: how it works. If you want to reduce bias: start with Observer bias → Spatial clumping → Repeatability. If you publish or analyze data: start with Limits → Aggregation → Export and citation. ¶Identification How identification works Disagreement and uncertainty When not to identify ¶Data quality and failure modes Data quality: Research Grade, bias, and failure modes Failure mode: observer bias Failure mode: spatial clumping Failure mode: popularity effects ¶Ethics, governance, and open science Sensitive species and obscured locations Extractive observing and community impact Civic and open science: resources and practices ¶Using data Limits: what iNaturalist data can and cannot support Aggregation and analysis Export and citation ¶Concepts Practitioner model Glossary ",
